g.text: You: "This is where I started off with my motor carriage... before sinking it in the sea."
You: This is where I started off with my motor carriage.
You: This is the point of departure of the motor carriage that crashed into the Samaran Butter sign, right?
Kim Kitsuragi: "Yes, it is. Well," he gestures toward the gaping hole in the fence, "you did provide us with a very convenient access point to the crime scene."
Visual Calculus: The tyre tracks were left here by an unknown event that took place some days ago. It's a message, written in the language of burnt rubber.
Perception (Sight): Cop habit. You look at everything.
You: I think I got it. [Leave.]
You: "A car drove through the fence."
You: "Is this connected to the case?"
Kim Kitsuragi: "You are correct. This is a rather motor carriage-friendly city."
Authority: The hole in this fence doesn't look *that* huge.
Kim Kitsuragi: The lieutenant follows the tracks with his gaze. "That's plausible. A similar... reckless abandon seems to be in evidence."
Visual Calculus: ...before heading south. Must have been in a hurry.
Perception (Sight): Hard to say. Your vision is blurred and you are having difficulty concentrating thanks to your relentless hangover.
Inland Empire: Somehow that makes you feel... scared. You don't know why.
Visual Calculus: The tracks are as they have ever been. A bit more worn, perhaps. Fortunately, the street sweeper still hasn't noticed their presence.
You: "This is the point of departure of the vehicle that crashed into the Samaran Butter sign."
Visual Calculus: No, these tracks are not interesting at all. Let the street sweeper just sweep them away.
Interfacing: As a matter of fact, you don't even know why you stopped here. You would never drive recklessly like this. And you don't have a car.
Authority: He was exaggerating. People blame *cops* for everything that goes wrong in the world. This has nothing to do with you.
You: Why am I looking at this?
Visual Calculus: The driver proceeded to back out of the yard, barely stopping before hitting the adjacent building...
Visual Calculus: You could *follow* the tracks south. There seems to be a canal there. See where they went. (If you find the time.)
Visual Calculus: Some of that rubber stuck to the tiles right in front of the Whirling-in-Rags. This is point A. The driver started there...
Logic: This isn't case-related, you think.
Visual Calculus: Yes. And ended up half-sunken in the sea. You must have been drunk when you left off.
Kim Kitsuragi: "No wonder the cafeteria manager seemed frustrated when he was giving us directions to the yard."
You: What kind of vehicle drove through here?
Inland Empire: An ominous warning of bad things ahead.
Visual Calculus: ...and then accelerated straight into the fence.
...and then accelerated straight into the fence. Left a hole *big enough for the Franconigerian cavalry,* according to the cafeteria manager.
...and then accelerated straight into the fence. Left a hole *big enough for the Franconigerian cavalry,* according to the cafeteria manager. (Why that pang of guilt again?)
Visual Calculus: Why yes it is! Good connection.
Kim Kitsuragi: "Well," he gestures toward the gaping hole in the fence, "you did provide us with a very convenient access point to the crime scene."
Perception (Sight): You see a set of tyre tracks in the brown slush that covers the plaza mosaic.
You: The hole is not that impressive.
Kim Kitsuragi: "I'm not sure... there are plenty of traffic accidents waiting to happen in Martinaise. With the jam right here on the roundabout. I would keep them separate."
